<Article
  title="How to Tell If a Game Guide Is Actually Trustworthy"
  description="Most guides on the internet are outdated copies of copies. Use these quick checks to decide whether you should follow any guide before you ruin a run."
  kicker="Player Guide"
  date="2026-06-24"
  heading="How to Spot Trustworthy Guides"
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="sec">
    <p>You’ve been there: you follow a popular guide, the numbers are wrong, the route doesn’t exist anymore, or the strategy was patched out weeks ago. Search engines reward good SEO, not good data. Here’s a field checklist you can apply in under a minute.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>1. Does it even mention a version or date?</h2>
    <p>If a guide has no version number and no “last updated” date, the author is implicitly saying “I have no idea if this is still correct.” Good guides are explicit about the patch they were written for.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>2. Test it with one fact you already know</h2>
    <p>Pick something you are personally confident about (a specific monster behavior, an item value, a role ability). Look it up in the guide.</p>
    <ul class="kv">
      <li>If even the thing you know is wrong → the rest is probably garbage.</li>
      <li>If the detail you know is precise and matches what you’ve seen → higher chance the author actually plays the game.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>3. Cross-check two or three independent sources</h2>
    <p>Compare the same data point across sources. When multiple sources agree on an outdated number, that usually means they all copied the same bad source. The one that shows a recent update date and explains changes is usually the one worth trusting.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>4. How does it handle uncertainty?</h2>
    <p>This is the single best signal. Any complex game has data that is genuinely hard to confirm. Good authors say “this is estimated from X observations” or “community data conflicts here”. Authors who are 100% confident on everything are usually just copying confidently.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>5. Bonus red flags</h2>
    <ul class="kv">
      <li>Identical phrasing across 6 different sites (copy-paste network)</li>
      <li>No mention of game mode or difficulty the data applies to</li>
      <li>Images that are clearly from a different patch (UI changed, values in screenshots don’t match text)</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</Article>
